00:43:02,232 --> 00:43:04,454
Now this led us to some design principles.

726
00:43:05,115 --> 00:43:07,457
And I may say up front that we broke all of these,

727
00:43:07,597 --> 00:43:09,198
and that is why we have them.

728
00:43:10,699 --> 00:43:11,220
Lesson learned.

729
00:43:12,747 --> 00:43:15,008
Information should never be a prerequisite for progression.

730
00:43:15,628 --> 00:43:17,769
An example could be in the Helmut Kruger opportunity

731
00:43:17,809 --> 00:43:19,329
where you hear about the meeting.

732
00:43:20,650 --> 00:43:25,552
In the beginning, when we did this,

733
00:43:26,473 --> 00:43:28,734
Kruger would only drop the phone if you

734
00:43:28,774 --> 00:43:29,834
had heard about the meeting.

735
00:43:30,678 --> 00:43:32,820
There would be no phone unless you knew about it.

736
00:43:33,621 --> 00:43:35,262
That's not a cool way to fix things.

737
00:43:36,002 --> 00:43:37,464
Of course, we fixed it very quickly,

738
00:43:37,904 --> 00:43:40,406
made sure that wouldn't happen again, because that

739
00:43:40,446 --> 00:43:41,987
doesn't support consistency.

740
00:43:42,047 --> 00:43:42,888
That was one of our rules.

741
00:43:44,329 --> 00:43:45,530
And be very mindful of this.

742
00:43:46,090 --> 00:43:47,471
If you are doing anything similar,

743
00:43:48,492 --> 00:43:50,573
make sure that you use real things in the world.

744
00:43:50,694 --> 00:43:51,354
Use items.

745
00:43:51,554 --> 00:43:52,375
Use anything else.

746
00:43:52,415 --> 00:43:55,337
Just don't use information if you want this playground.

747
00:43:57,319 --> 00:43:59,500
Opportunities should let go before they kill.

748
00:44:00,655 --> 00:44:02,375
Again, I kind of mentioned it before.

749
00:44:02,395 --> 00:44:04,036
We want this autonomous player.

750
00:44:04,056 --> 00:44:05,957
We wanted them to have fun.

751
00:44:06,897 --> 00:44:11,640
But this also brings me back to the whole fail condition part.

752
00:44:13,760 --> 00:44:15,821
Let's say that we told you to kill Dahlia.

753
00:44:16,742 --> 00:44:18,683
Well, we told you to kill her in a very specific way.

754
00:44:18,703 --> 00:44:22,504
And we told you to listen to some of the conversation

755
00:44:22,564 --> 00:44:23,725
and then stand up and shoot her.

756
00:44:24,565 --> 00:44:26,506
That means that you have to fail the opportunity

757
00:44:26,766 --> 00:44:28,607
if the player does anything else.

758
00:44:29,717 --> 00:44:32,181
And that is kind of a, that's a tall order.

759
00:44:32,521 --> 00:44:33,784
And you shouldn't do that to your players.

760
00:44:34,264 --> 00:44:36,007
So think about what you're actually doing

761
00:44:36,027 --> 00:44:37,189
when you make these type of guides,

762
00:44:37,269 --> 00:44:39,733
because you may end up giving your player

763
00:44:39,753 --> 00:44:40,715
a really bad experience.

764
00:44:43,494 --> 00:44:45,815
The opportunity should always be available, even without the guide.

765
00:44:45,835 --> 00:44:50,756
Yeah, that's just, again, the consistency.

766
00:44:51,536 --> 00:44:53,597
You don't want the guide to be dictating anything.

767
00:44:53,657 --> 00:44:55,617
We don't want the story to dictate anything.

768
00:44:55,817 --> 00:44:58,158
We want the level to dictate it.

769
00:44:58,178 --> 00:45:02,159
We want the player to be able to be in control, and not the other way around.

770
00:45:03,558 --> 00:45:05,760
